  "verdict": "DOES THE DISCRETE SUBSTRATE HIDE ITS PREFERRED FRAME? SPLIT ANSWER \u2014 a productive partial-negative. TEMPORAL SECTOR (Part A, analytic from the substrate's own lattice dispersion, non-circular): the moving internal clock omega_co satisfies omega_co*gamma = M (rest frequency) to <0.5% at low k (time dilation EMERGES, dilation_holds_lowk=True), breaking at the LIV onset v_g~0.5701 (k~0.814) \u2014 same grid scale as Phase-2/4. So the CLOCK hides at low energy. SPATIAL SECTOR (Part B, evolved soliton, no SR assumed): this is where it does NOT cleanly work. The discrete soliton is PEIERLS-NABARRO PINNED (pn_pinning=True): v~0 for k=0.2/0.4/0.6, it barely moves until k=0.9 \u2014 a discrete soliton RESISTS free boosting, which is the preferred frame showing through in the SPATIAL sector at LOWER velocity than the dispersion-LIV onset. The width it shows shrinks FASTER than gamma (profile self-adjustment, not Lorentz contraction; contraction_clean=False), and the soliton's internal-frequency readout is unreliable (rest omega_co~0, not M \u2014 the boosted soliton is not a clean internal-clock eigenstate). So length contraction + free boostability is NOT demonstrated. SO WHAT (honest): the make-or-break question does NOT cleanly pass. The temporal half (time dilation) hides; the SPATIAL half (contraction / free motion) is exactly where the classic discrete-substrate Lorentz hurdle (GPT's caution) shows up concretely \u2014 PN pinning, the known obstruction to Lorentz invariance in discrete soliton lattices. The universal clock is HALF-hidden: invisible in time, visible in space (and earlier than the LIV scale). This is a real constraint, not a vindication: a viable substrate must use a discreteness that avoids PN pinning (translationally-invariant discretizations exist; this naive lattice is not one). Bucket 0 unchanged. PRODUCTIVE NEGATIVE: it localizes the problem to the spatial sector and names the fix-direction."
